No need to test the snippet. Code was tested just by running and it prevents IndexError. However, the confirmation message is not being received on temporary mail (not my problem, but we will try to determine the error and find a new solution)
Remove forced Streamlit version. You're breaking other software that uses GPT4Free and Streamlit for their own apps by forcing this.

The error you are encountering is related to attempting to use the default asyncio event loop within a non-main thread. asyncio expects you to use the default event loop only in the main thread.
To resolve this issue, asyncio.new_event_loop() was used instead of asyncio.get_event_loop() to create a new event loop for the current thread.

Overview:
This PR introduces Docker support to simplify the setup and usage of the gpt4free project, making it more accessible to developers and ensuring a consistent environment.
Changes:

Added Dockerfile to define the container environment.
Added docker-compose.yml for easy setup and orchestration.
Updated README.md with instructions on how to use Docker to set up and run the project.

How to Test:

Ensure Docker and docker-compose are installed.
Clone this branch.
Run docker-compose up from the project root.
The application should be accessible at http://localhost:1337.

Please review and provide feedback. If there are any issues or improvements needed, I'm open to making the necessary changes. Thank you for considering this contribution!

This PR creates a unified g4f CLI that is able to run the gui or the interference api. This CLI has also been added to the setup.py console_scripts so that the gui and api are easily runnable once gpt4free is installed via pip.

When I started this project with Docker on my MacBook Pro M1 chip, I found that Chrome would get an error, probably because Chrome only supports the 4K Pagesize AMD64 platform, not Arm64. After investigating, the current seleniumnode/chrome image used by the dockerfile only supports amd64. The selenium community is already pushing for the arm64 merge SeleniumHQ/docker-selenium#1847. For the time being, we are using the base image seleniarm/node-chromium that supports both arm64 and amd64 to ensure dual-architecture support.
Currently, arm64 images support Pagesize 4k kernels, and there is no support plan for Pagesize 64k in the short term (Chrome does not support 64k Pagezie).
